reviews.text: For me, this is the best museum in Europe. So many fantastic works of art.

Remnants of the main synagogue of Barcelona. Do not expect an actual synagogue, the Jewish community was forcefully converted in 1391, and it's main sites thoroughly destroyed. 
What remains of Jewish memory in Barcelona is scattered, and easy to overlook.
The hidden gem here are the guided visits the synagogue provides in Spanish, English, Hebrew, etc. They will help you to understand jewish life in medieval Barcelona.
They charge to go in so we didn't get past the front room. Looks cool though.
Worth a visit, €3.50 donation to enter. Quite small but full of fantastic history and staff give short speech on the jewish history and how it links in with Barcelona.

I had the pleasure to photograph a beautiful intimate wedding in the old Synagogue. I loved the atmosphere, the staff was very friendly, all prepared till a small little details for a perfect celebration.

We was not able to find the place on our first visit to Barcelona. It was around midnight in the middle of October - very common time for Barcelona to be out and explore place around. We wanted to find the Ancient Synagogue to be able to come here again at the day time. Interesting to say, at we were not alone, there was another couple trying to find the place - no luck. We returned next year at the day time,  we did it! It was worth the time and money to know the background of the Call carrer (Jewish community location in Barcelona).

This church was built more than 150 years ago and hence has historical significance. Even though it is situated at a crowded junction, you can feel the peace once you walk down the path from the entrance to the church. On stepping into it you get to see a glimpse of an era that has been preserved. The peaceful and holy atmosphere is most evident in the afternoon which was the time I chose to visit it.

Right at the heart of the city, this church is a perfect location for worship. Tree covered campus, ample parking space, neatly maintained gardens and buildings. Church is pretty old, still with the old chairs and benches, same old walls and floor. Under renovation now, a new look is expected.

Resting place for the traffic police men while they're not very busy, a breathing space for them.

It was built in 1851, for the British Regiment stationed in Bangalore. 
Built in the English Renaissance style, the church can accommodate 
700 people and is regarded as the largest "military" church in southern India. 
It has a congregation of over 450 families
The church was consecrated on 25 July 1852 and opened on 8 August, 1852. 
The original estimate of the construction was ₹27,000 (US$380)
After Independence, the church was taken over by the Christian Indian Military personnel 
and their families. It was called Holy Trinity Garrison Pastorate then.
The walls were lined with ornate marble murals and tablets, which spoke about 
great men and women who toiled for the church. They Used to conduct many programs for youth especially Troika. They have a best team for youth. On March 10th they conducted the Peace Rally for the Pulwama Terrorist Attack. Really its a good experience for me. I Love this Church

When I moved to Bangalore, my fiancé was going here so he took me here. It was away from where we stay so we started checking other Tamil places nearby but now we are regularly going there. It’s worth traveling there. Best place to worship, such a nice priest. They have a good worshipping culture. You can feel Almighty’s presence there. #myfavchurch
Always a church with deep history and architecture gives a nostalgic feeling. This Tamil church surely is one of the churches which makes me feel at home and gives me a blessed experience.

After getting to know them better, I eat at least once per month at Tokyo Japanese Restaurant. The service is absolutely impecable, the food is great, and the quality is constant. You never get bad sushi, bad soup, or soggy tempura. The awesome fish selection, availability of Japanese beverages and the care and dedication towards the food and the customer makes me want to go there again and again.

I've been visiting this restaurant every once in a while for years. Today the service and quality of the food were amazing, as always (I didn't realize I hadn't left a review until now). 

This is one of the (unfortunately) very rare places I know of in Cluj where I am confident I won't be let down when I return, and that's why I prefer Tokyo over other places for special moments.

I've become more and more appreciative of places that are able to offer the same great food and service constantly, irrespective of the time of year or how busy the restaurant is. 

I've been to Tokyo on quiet afternoons or on days when every table was booked and I noticed no difference in the experience - and that's just one of the things I love about this restaurant.

The food tastes amazing, in particular the seafood is well prepared and always fresh, and you can have sakuramochi for desert! 

The menu is varied and can offer a great experience of Japanese cuisine. It's even possible to order dishes consisting of smaller portions of various entrees and deserts, a really nice idea for those of us who have a hard time deciding what to order.

The staff are always ready to offer a smile and good advice, and they seem to know everything there is to know about the menu.

The atmosphere is intimate and quiet, with airy rooms that take your mind off the cluttered city, and the music is soothing and not too loud. I've noticed people tend to speak in hushed tones, and that can be a welcome change from the usual types of places where you need to raise your voice over the music and over the voices of people at other tables, but you do need to be in the mood for it.

There is more I could say about Tokyo, but it's probably better to visit them and discover for yourselves a place that strives to offer perfection in the smallest details, and, at least in my opinion, achieves it.

Thank you for a wonderful evening and for the care and attention to details you always spoil us with.

I hope I am the first and the last one to rate this place. 

At first, we were asked to seat in the corner of the restaurant with no one coming to attend us for next ten minutes. 

Our waiter for the day - Prasanna was not at all the knowledgable on the menu. He didn't even bring the Drinks menu to us in the first place. After we insisted, he got us just one menu, seeing there are two people on the table.

We wanted to have Old Fashioned and Prasanna had no idea what that drink was. We were later informed that the restaurant ran out of bitter. How can a hotel like Taj run out of bitter ?  We settled for Kingfisher Beer. 

The dinner started off in a very disappointing way when we were served some tasteless Anitpasti that can only be compared to Corn Fluid. The Main Course tasted equally bad.

For the main course, I ordered a Spaghetti and I made pretty clear that I my pasta needs to be a Spaghetti but I was served Linguine. Again, there was no communication in terms of how our food and our experience was. Moreover, our waiter got us one plate and kept the other guest waiting for next ten minutes. In a restaurant, you always get two plates together. That's restaurant 101. 

This was very disappointing experience. And, I was charged Rs 3600 for this experience. We left the food on the plate and walked away and no one even enquired about that. 

If you still wanna go to this place. Be my guest.

We arrived early afternoon and asked to sit inside, there were maybe 2 guests in whole establishment. The waitress told us not possible as reserved tables, we left after food and there were still just 2 guests.
What is also poor is my friends food arrived 15 minutes before mine, she had almost finished eating before my meal arrived. How difficult for even a basic student chef or cook to start for example a steak, which takes twice time as salmon for example so both meals arrive same time. 
So not good experience and do not recommend. 
Shame as food was nice.
